    {
        "content": "<p>Is it possible to use both Isabelles F-Division and the euclidean division for Integers in the same theory?<br>\nOr would this require redefining one of the two as a separate function?</p>",
        "id": 420045114,
        "sender_full_name": "Nils Buchholz",
        "timestamp": 1707225432
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What is \"F-division\"?</p>",
        "id": 420632065,
        "sender_full_name": "Manuel Eberl",
        "timestamp": 1707477690
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Division that always rounds down.<br>\nSo 5/2 = 2 and -5/2 = -3 etc.</p>",
        "id": 420886660,
        "sender_full_name": "Nils Buchholz",
        "timestamp": 1707654762
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's what Isabelle/HOL's normal <code>div</code> operator already does.</p>",
        "id": 421842266,
        "sender_full_name": "Manuel Eberl",
        "timestamp": 1708083577
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I assume the alternative would be to always round to 0? We don't have one like that, I think. If you want that you'll have to define one yourself and it will be separate from the normal one.</p>",
        "id": 421842414,
        "sender_full_name": "Manuel Eberl",
        "timestamp": 1708083643
    },
